Q1.A single host sends TCP SYN packets to ports 21, 22, 23, 25, 53, 80, and 443 on the same server within one second.
What attack is occurring?
SYN Port Scan

Q2.One host sends ICMP Echo Requests to every IP address from 192.168.1.1 to 192.168.1.254.
Ping Sweep

Q3.Thousands of TCP SYN packets are sent to port 80, but very few ACK packets return.
SYN Flood

Q4.A host sends UDP packets to ports 53, 69, 123, 161, and 500 on another host.
UDP Scan

Q5.Multiple unsolicited ARP replies claim that the gateway IP belongs to the attacker's MAC address.
ARP Poisoning

Q6.Thousands of DNS queries contain long, random-looking subdomains.
DNS Tunneling

Q7.Hundreds of FTP login attempts fail before one succeeds.
FTP Brute Force

Q8.A web server receives 500 POST requests to /login.php from the same client.
HTTP Brute Force

Q9.One client repeatedly attempts SSH authentication with different usernames.
SSH Brute Force

Q10.A host accesses numerous SMB shares and requests system information.
SMB Enumeration

Q11.Packets with FIN, PSH, and URG flags set are sent to many destination ports.
TCP Christmas Scan

Q12.TCP packets contain only the FIN flag while probing multiple ports.
FIN Scan

Q13.TCP packets have no flags set.
NULL Scan

Q14.The attacker sends only ACK packets to determine firewall rules.
ACK Scan

Q15.Thousands of ICMP Echo Requests are sent to a single victim.
ICMP Flood

Q16.The victim sends an unusually high number of TCP Reset packets after receiving connection attempts.
Port Scan

Q17.A host requests many domain names that do not exist.
DNS Enumeration

Q18.A single client opens hundreds of HTTP connections without completing requests.
Slow HTTP Attack (Slowloris-like)

Q19.One host sends DHCP Discover messages with different MAC addresses.
DHCP Starvation

Q20.A host repeatedly connects to ports 80 and 443 while sending unusual TLS handshake messages.
TLS Enumeration

Q21.A host scans all devices in the subnet using ARP Requests.
ARP Scan

Q22.A DNS server sends responses much larger than the corresponding requests.
DNS Amplification

Q23.Many TCP retransmissions occur while the server is under heavy traffic.
Possible DoS Attack

Q24.A client sends repeated login attempts to a Telnet service.
Telnet Brute Force

Q25.A single IP communicates with nearly every device on the local network within a few seconds.
Network Discovery / Host Sweep


Q26.After analyzing the provided Wireshark capture, what attack is being performed?
SYN Flood Attack

Q27.The capture shows one source host sending SYN packets to many destination ports on the same server. What activity is occurring?
Port Scanning

Q28.Multiple unsolicited ARP replies are observed, each claiming the same IP address belongs to the attacker's MAC address. Which attack is this?
ARP Poisoning

Q29.The capture contains thousands of ICMP Echo Requests in a short period. Which attack is most likely?
ICMP Flood (Ping Flood)

Q30.The capture contains unusually long DNS queries with random-looking subdomains sent repeatedly to the same domain. What is the most likely attack?
DNS Tunneling

Q31.Many failed FTP login attempts from the same IP address are followed by a successful login. Which attack is indicated?
FTP Brute Force Attack

Q32.A web server receives hundreds of POST requests to the login page from the same client within a minute. What attack is most likely?
HTTP Brute Force Attack

Q33.A host attempts connections to multiple SMB shares and issues numerous SMB information requests. What is the activity?
SMB Enumeration

Q34.Packets with the FIN, PSH, and URG flags set are observed while probing multiple ports. Which scan is being used?
TCP Christmas Scan

Q35.A host sends UDP packets to many destination ports and receives ICMP Port Unreachable responses for most of them. What is occurring?
UDP Scan
